---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
import Ph from '../components/Ph.astro';
import Figure from '../components/Figure.astro';
import teamPhoto from '../assets/photos/placeholder-team.svg';
import actionPhoto from '../assets/photos/placeholder-action.svg';
---

<Base
  title="Work — Twenty-five years in the second seat | Tom Vranas"
  description="Track record: seats held across operations, people, marketing, and innovation — and a featured case study of three add-on integrations through the Zentro platform."
>
  <section class="section">
    <div class="container">
      <p class="eyebrow">Track Record</p>
      <h1 style="margin-top: 0.9rem;">Twenty-five years in the second seat.</h1>

      <h2 style="margin-top: 3rem;">Seats held</h2>
      <ul class="seats" style="margin-top: 1.25rem;">
        <li>
          <span class="seat__role">Co-Founder &amp; COO</span> &middot; Bulqit &middot;
          Marketplace / home services
        </li>
        <li>
          <span class="seat__role">Chief of Staff, Innovation &amp; People</span> &middot; Zentro
          Internet &middot; Broadband &mdash; operating lead through 3 acquisitions and exit to
          Greystar/GIP
        </li>
        <li>
          <span class="seat__role">Chief of Staff, Innovation &amp; People</span> &middot; Everywhere
          Wireless &middot; Broadband &mdash; through exit to MC Partners
        </li>
        <li>
          <span class="seat__role">Chief People Officer</span> &middot; <Ph>[COMPANY]</Ph> &middot;
          <Ph>[industry]</Ph>
        </li>
        <li>
          <span class="seat__role">VP, Innovation &amp; Culture</span> &middot; Everywhere Wireless
        </li>
        <li>
          <span class="seat__role"><Ph>[Call center build]</Ph></span> &middot;
          The Princeton Review &mdash; built and ran <Ph>[X]</Ph>-seat operation
        </li>
        <li>
          <span class="seat__role"><Ph>[National marketing role]</Ph></span> &middot;
          <Ph>[COMPANY]</Ph>
        </li>
      </ul>

      <p style="margin-top: 1.75rem;">
        The pattern across all of them: companies in transition, a strong-vision leader in the
        first seat, and a machine that needed building. Industry changes; the job doesn&rsquo;t.
      </p>

      <div style="margin-top: 2.5rem;">
        <Figure
          src={teamPhoto}
          alt="Placeholder for a photo of Tom Vranas with one of his operating teams"
          caption="[Team photo — drop in src/assets/photos/, then real caption: company, team, year]"
          pending
        />
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="container">
      <p class="eyebrow">Featured Case Study</p>
      <h2 style="margin-top: 0.9rem;">
        Three acquisitions. One platform. Zero broken promises to customers.
      </h2>

      <p style="margin-top: 1.5rem;">
        Between 2019 and <Ph>2024 [confirm]</Ph>, Zentro Internet executed a buy-and-build
        strategy in Chicago-area broadband, acquiring three competitors while continuing organic
        growth. I led integration as Chief of Staff, Innovation &amp; People. The platform sold to
        Greystar / GIP in <Ph>2024 [confirm]</Ph>. This is the deepest test of the operating skill
        &mdash; making two companies run as one &mdash; and how it worked.
      </p>

      <h3 style="margin-top: 2.5rem;">The situation</h3>
      <p style="margin-top: 0.7rem;">
        <Ph>
          [2&ndash;3 sentences per deal or in aggregate: subscriber counts, network footprint,
          team sizes, what made each one hard. PLACEHOLDER &mdash; pull from the case study
          draft.]
        </Ph>
      </p>

      <h3 style="margin-top: 2.5rem;">The approach</h3>
      <p style="margin-top: 0.7rem;">
        Integration isn&rsquo;t a project plan; it&rsquo;s triage plus rhythm. Before each close,
        I ran an operational audit &mdash; billing systems, network architecture, customer
        contracts, team structure, financial hygiene. Day one, the integration cadence started:
        weekly business reviews, a single scorecard, clear owners for every workstream. The goal
        was never speed for its own sake. It was protecting what we paid for: the customers, the
        revenue, and the people worth keeping.
      </p>

      <div style="margin-top: 2rem;">
        <Figure
          src={actionPhoto}
          alt="Placeholder for a photo of Tom Vranas leading an all-hands or integration review"
          caption="[Action shot — all-hands / integration review — real caption: event, company, year]"
          pending
        />
      </div>

      <p style="margin-top: 2rem;">
        <strong>The three things that decide whether an integration works:</strong>
      </p>

      <div class="proof-blocks" style="margin-top: 1.25rem;">
        <div class="proof-block">
          <h3>Systems before sentiment.</h3>
          <p>
            Merge billing, support, and network operations first. Culture conversations land
            better when paychecks and customer tickets aren&rsquo;t broken.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="proof-block">
          <h3>One scorecard, fast.</h3>
          <p>
            The acquired team joins the operating rhythm in week one, not quarter two. Nothing
            signals &ldquo;you&rsquo;re part of this now&rdquo; like being on the same dashboard.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="proof-block">
          <h3>Retention is an operations problem.</h3>
          <p>
            Customer churn post-acquisition is rarely about the brand changing. It&rsquo;s about
            service quality dipping while everyone&rsquo;s distracted. We measured it weekly and
            staffed against it.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <h3 style="margin-top: 2.5rem;">The results</h3>
      <p style="margin-top: 0.7rem;">
        <Ph>
          [PLACEHOLDER: churn held at X% through integration windows / synergy targets hit by
          month X / retained X% of key staff / platform EBITDA grew from X to Y / sold to
          Greystar-GIP at [outcome]. Use only numbers you can defend in a room with Ryan.]
        </Ph>
      </p>

      <h3 style="margin-top: 2.5rem;">What this means for your deal</h3>
      <p style="margin-top: 0.7rem;">
        If you&rsquo;re a sponsor or CEO with an add-on closing &mdash; or a platform where the
        last integration never quite finished &mdash; the playbook above is repeatable. I work as
        a contract integration lead or interim operating executive: defined scope, defined
        timeline, hand-off to your permanent team.
      </p>

      <p style="margin-top: 2rem;">
        <a class="btn" href="/contact">Discuss your deal</a>
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>
</Base>
